Tris voice of criticism has unanimonsly fixed on this book, along with the Fourth and Sixth, as affording the best evidence of the true greatness of Virgil. Donatus says that the poet himself chose these three books to read to Augustus as a specimen of his work. This may or may not be true, but it indicates at any, rate the judgrnent passed by antiquity3 and medem opinion has not been slow to ratify the verdict.
